=== Understanding German Constant Clusters

There a several frequently occurring German consonant clusters that correspond to a single sound (phoneme). Below are examples:

* **sch**
** Scheumann: pass:[<pre style="font-family: '18th Century Kurrent Text'; font-size: 4em;">Scheumann</pre>]
** Gröschel: pass:[<pre style="font-family: '18th Century Kurrent Text'; font-size: 4em;">Gröschel</pre>]
** **Note:** When the "sch" was written with a quick hand, the "c" often got ommitted.
* **ch**
** Achem Seifert: pass:[<pre style="font-family: '18th Century Kurrent Text'; font-size: 4em;">Achem Seifert</pre>]
** Alois Albrecht: pass:[<pre style="font-family: '18th Century Kurrent Text'; font-size: 4em;">Alois Albrecht</pre>]
* **St** similiar to an **N** but with **t** intersecting the down stroke of the **N**:
** Stille: image:stille.jpg[]
* *tz*
** **jetzt**: note the extra final 't': pass:[<pre style="font-family: '18th Century Kurrent Text'; font-size: 4em;">jetzt</pre>]
* *pf*
** *pfeifen* -- to whistle: pass:[<pre style="font-family: '18th Century Kurrent Text'; font-size: 4em;">pfeifen</pre>]


